    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-06-04T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-06-04T23:00:00-05:00" n="246"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d246">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/1946</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_RPS1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Reinsch</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-06-05T12:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 5, 1918, noon</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 3.52 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>My telegram of May 30, 12 noon.<note n="2" xml:id="d246fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_181">p. 181</ref>.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SGG1">Semenov</persName> expects two battalions Japanese
                    troops, called unofficial assistance. He has agreed with <persName
                        corresp="#p_HGDL1">Horvat</persName> on this policy and financial support,
                    eliminating <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1">Kolchak</persName>. The latter and
                        <persName>Orlov</persName> devote themselves to recovering Amur Province,
                    where sentiment is becoming increasingly hostile to Bolsheviks. <persName
                        corresp="#p_SGG1">Semenov</persName> compensation to Japan believed to
                    comprise exclusive mining, fishery rights Amur Province and dismantling
                    Vladivostok fortifications.</p>
                <p>All American representatives in Siberia are agreed that Allied intervention is
                    absolutely demanded; Siberia will be in German control unless immediate action
                    is taken. Joint action desirable because of Russian fear of Japan. Presence of
                    Czecho-Slovaks can be utilized. American force of 10,000 considered
                    sufficient.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RPS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Reinsch</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
